    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right that the logs often look clean even when the inventory is missing, which is a classic sign of \"ghost items\" caused by a misconfigured User Interface (UI) or a specific workflow loop. One very common culprit in Rotterdam warehouses is the \"bin-to-bin\" transfer error, where a picker scans a box into a bin, but the system thinks the box is still in the previous location because the scan wasn't fully committed before the picker moved on.\n\nAnother subtle possibility is the \"bin overflow\" issue, where a picker scans an item into a bin that is already full, but the system fails to deduct the item from the source bin due to a timeout or a corrupted transaction record. This is particularly common with high-volume items like the Resistor Pack.\n\nTo solve this, you should also check if the picking software is using a \"greedy\" algorithm that auto-fills bins without verifying the exact quantity remaining, which can lead to the system thinking an item is still available when it has already been physically removed. A good workaround is to implement a \"confirm and close\" step before a bin is marked as complete, forcing the system to validate the entire transaction before moving to the next task.",
